The South African Medical Association has accepted an apology from its Chair, Angelique Coetzee. It relates to racist remarks during an interview where she slammed medical schools' admission processes. Dr Mvuyisi Mzukwa, who is on SAMA's Board of Directors, speaks to eNCA. Courtesy #DStv403 #eNCA JOHANNESBURG - The SA Medical Association has accepted an apology from its chair, Angelique Coetzee. It relates to racist remarks during an interview where she slammed medical schools' admission processes. Coetzee said acceptance criteria is highly politicised. READ: SA Medical Association gives govt an ultimatum She also said race played a more significant determining factor than matric results. She has since apologised to the board, saying she now understands the processes are far more complex. SAMA says it understands the outrage over her statements and distances itself from them. The body says all candidates are accepted based on merit and ability.